Are there any plans, or is it even possible, to support NativeLibrary in dotnet standard?

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.runtime.interopservices.nativelibrary?view=netcore-3.1

I have a dotnet standard 2.1 library that needs to load a c++ library, but we want to support multiple versions of the library (linux and windows).

Example usage: 
```C#
static class NativeMethods
{
	private const string LibraryName = "something";
	static NativeMethods()
	{
		NativeLibrary.SetDllImportResolver(typeof(NativeMethods).Assembly, ImportResolver);
	}
	private static IntPtr ImportResolver(string libraryName, Assembly assembly, DllImportSearchPath? searchPath)
	{
		IntPtr libHandle = IntPtr.Zero;
		if (libraryName == NativeMethods.LibraryName)
		{
			string library;
			if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.Linux))
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.so";	
			} 
			else if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.dylib";
			}
			else
			{
				library = "libsomething_c.dll";
			}
			var libraryLoaded = NativeLibrary.TryLoad(library, assembly, DllImportSearchPath.AssemblyDirectory, out libHandle);
			if (!libraryLoaded)
			{
				throw new Exception($"Unable to Load Library: {library}");
			}
		}
		return libHandle;
	}
```

Alternatively, is there another way to load a cross platform C++ code in a dotnet standard?

**Version Used**: VS 2019 version 16.8.2, master (d0d9a59) on SharpLab

**Steps to Reproduce**:

[Compile code like the following:](https://sharplab.io/#v2:EYLgtghgzgLgpgJwDQxAN0QSwGYE8A+AAgEwAEAQtHALABQA3nac6QA4ID28AxvACalCAFlIBZABQBKUvQC+debTolSAESwYBIClTqNaLQWQBycWHD5MW+w4eFiImAHbiOwAFZxepDpKu2ZfwCWcXF1BExNSV8AOglJAG4g4NJQyig4aMk4qSSDYMVDRVkgA)

```c#
class Base
{
    protected void M() {}
}

class Derived : Base
{
    class Nested
    {
        void Main(object o)
        {
            ((Derived)o).M();
            ((Base)o).M();
        }
    }
}
```

**Actual Behavior**:

The second call to `M` produces the following error:

> error CS1540: Cannot access protected member 'Base.M()' via a qualifier of type 'Base'; the qualifier must be of type 'Derived.Nested' (or derived from it)

**Expected Behavior**:

The second call to `M` produces the following error:

> error CS1540: Cannot access protected member 'Base.M()' via a qualifier of type 'Base'; the qualifier must be of type 'Derived' (or derived from it)

The type `Derived.Nested` is not part of the inheritance hierarchy, so it doesn't make sense to mention it here, the type that should be mentioned is `Derived`.

Also, I think it would be better if the error message didn't use the term "qualifier", since I think it's not going to be familiar for many developers.

